    "reasoning": "The problem requires implementing a finite state machine (FSM) to detect PS/2 mouse protocol messages. Each message consists of three bytes, and the start of a message is indicated by in[3] being high. The FSM must discard bytes until it finds one with in[3]=1, then count the next two bytes to complete the 3-byte message. When the third byte is received, it should assert 'done'. The states needed are: IDLE (waiting for start of message), BYTE1 (first byte received), and BYTE2 (second byte received). We use localparam to define these states for clarity. All signals are declared as logic. Sequential logic is triggered on positive edge of clk and reset is synchronous active-high. An initial block is used to initialize the state register to IDLE.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input clk,\n    input reset,\n    input [7:0] in,\n    output logic done\n);\n\n    // Define states\n    localparam IDLE   = 2'b00;\n    localparam BYTE1  = 2'b01;\n    localparam BYTE2  = 2'b10;\n\n    // State register\n    logic [1:0] state;\n    logic [1:0] state_next;\n\n    // Initialize state\n    initial begin\n        state <= IDLE;\n    end\n\n    // Sequential logic\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (reset)\n            state <= IDLE;\n        else\n            state <= state_next;\n    end\n\n    // Next state logic\n    always @(*) begin\n        case (state)\n            IDLE: begin\n                if (in[3])\n                    state_next = BYTE1;\n                else\n                    state_next = IDLE;\n            end\n            BYTE1: begin\n                state_next = BYTE2;\n            end\n            BYTE2: begin\n                state_next = IDLE;\n            end\n        endcase\n    end\n\n    // Output logic\n    always @(*) begin\n        case (state)\n            IDLE:   done = 1'b0;\n            BYTE1:  done = 1'b0;\n            BYTE2:  done = 1'b1;\n        endcase\n    end\n\nendmodule"
}
